Pour 300ml cold @water{300%ml}(salted) into a #medium pot{} with a #tight-fitting lid{}.
Stir in the @rice{150%g} and bring to the boil.
Once boiling, lower the heat to medium, cover, and cook for ~{10%minutes}.

Remove the pot from the heat.
Keep covered for ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @shallot{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced).
Trim the @green beans{150%g}(trimmed, chopped into thirds).
Peel and grate the @garlic{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).
Roughly chop the @coriander{5%g}(roughly chopped, stalks and all).

Place a pan over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.
Once hot, add the @prawns{180%g}. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste} and cook for ~{4-5%minutes}.
Once cooked, remove the pan from the heat.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw prawns. Prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Once the prawns are cooked, add the shallot and cook until softened, stirring frequently, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add the garlic and @curry powder{2%sachets} and stir to coat the prawns. Cook for ~{1%minute}.
Pour in @water{100%ml} along with the @vegetable stock{1%sachet}.
Add the green beans, bring to the boil, then reduce the heat to medium.
Cover the pan with a lid or some #foil{}.
Simmer until the green beans are tender, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Once the green beans are tender, remove the lid from the pan and stir in the @creme fraiche{110%g} and @cranberry chutney{1%sachet}.
Bring to the boil, then remove the pan from the heat.
Stir through half the coriander.
Taste and season with salt and pepper if desired.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and divide between #bowls{}.
Top with the prawn curry.
Finish with a sprinkling of the remaining coriander.